# Express & Node.js — Middleware & Auth (Part 3)

## asyncHandler and error handling

*All patterns apply to both TypeScript and JavaScript. Omit type annotations for plain JS.*

- Use **async/await**; wrap route handlers with `asyncHandler` or try/catch.
- Centralized error middleware catches all errors. Never leave unhandled rejections.
- Consistent error shape: `{ success: false, code: string, message: string }`. Include stack only in dev.
- Use custom error classes with `statusCode` so error middleware can map to apiResponseTemplate.

```ts
// utils/errors.ts
class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(message: string, public statusCode: number = 500) {
    super(message);
    this.name = this.constructor.name;
    Error.captureStackTrace(this, this.constructor);
  }
}
class NotFoundError extends AppError { constructor(msg = 'Not found') { super(msg, 404); } }
class ValidationError extends AppError { constructor(msg: string, public errors?: unknown) { super(msg, 400); } }
```

```ts
// Error middleware (4 params required for Express to recognize it)
app.use((err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {
  const status = err instanceof AppError ? err.statusCode : 500;
  res.status(status).json({
    success: false,
    code: err.name || 'INTERNAL_ERROR',
    message: err.message,
    ...(process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development' && { stack: err.stack }),
  });
});

// asyncHandler (JS: const asyncHandler = (fn) => (req, res, next) => ...)
export const asyncHandler = (fn: RequestHandler) => (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) =>
  Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);
```

## Middleware order

**Order:** requestId → helmet → cors → json → rateLimit → csrf (if cookies) → routes → 404 → errorHandler.

| Middleware | Purpose |
|------------|---------|
| requestId | Generate/forward `X-Request-Id`; set `req.id` |
| helmet | Security headers |
| cors | Allowed origins only (never `*` in prod) |
| json | `express.json({ limit })` |
| rateLimit | express-rate-limit |
| csrf | When using cookies/sessions; skip for JWT-only |
| notFound | 404 for unknown routes |
| errorHandler | Central error middleware |

```js
// server.js
require('dotenv').config();
const app = require('./app');
const { config } = require('./config/env');
const server = app.listen(config.port, () => console.log(`Listening on ${config.port}`));
process.on('SIGTERM', () => { server.close(() => process.exit(0)); });
```

```js
// app.js
const app = express();
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.set('trust proxy', 1);
app.use(requestId);
app.use(helmet());
app.use(cors({ origin: config.corsOrigin }));
app.use(express.json({ limit: config.bodyLimit ?? '10mb' }));
app.use(rateLimit);
if (config.useCsrf) app.use(csrf);
app.use('/api/v1', v1Router);
app.use(notFound);
app.use(errorHandler);
```

## Auth middleware

- Validate JWT (or session); attach `req.user`. Use `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.
- Optional auth: middleware sets `req.user` only when token present; use `requireAuth` for protected routes.

**JWT best practices:**
- Set expiry (`exp`); short-lived access tokens (e.g. 15min) + refresh tokens.
- Do not store sensitive data in payload (base64, not encrypted).
- Verify `alg`; use RS256 when possible.
- Strong `JWT_SECRET` (min 32 chars); rotate on compromise.

**Password handling:**
- Hash with **bcrypt** (min 10 rounds) or **argon2**; never plain text.
- Do not log passwords; exclude from error messages.

## Security

- Helmet, CORS, rate limiting, body size limit, trust proxy when behind reverse proxy.
- Auth via middleware; never trust client for auth.
- HTTPS in production; no secrets in code or logs; mask in logs.
